<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="20" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1644,2029]" pageId="1" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,331,1968,1992]" pageId="1" pageNumber="20">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[828,903,1968,1992]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="20">nivalis</emphasis>
” meaning “snow-like”, which refers to 
<typeStatus box="[1357,1405,1969,1993]" pageId="1" pageNumber="20">type</typeStatus>
of the genus having spots and dust on its tegmina. The gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,248]" pageId="2" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,152,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="21">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new genus is placed into the tribe Nephesini by the following combination of characteristics: medium in size; tegmina no more than two times as long as broad, claval vein and basal clavus not elevated; postocular eminence conical, not ridged; antennal segment II not extending beyond anterior margin of gena.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
